   =20
 =20
If you are a high-powered trader at a big investment bank, two things that =
might happen are:=09You might make $600 million for your bank this year, or=
=09You might lose $600 million for your bank this year.Neither is very like=
ly, particularly not in this more boring post-crisis world, but either is p=
ossible. If you make $600 million that=E2=80=99s good and you=E2=80=99ll ge=
t a huge bonus. If you lose $600 million that=E2=80=99s bad and you=E2=80=
=99ll=C2=A0probably=C2=A0get fired, though it depends, and anyway you=E2=80=
=99ll have a cool war story that will  quickly get you  another big job som=
ewhere else. There is a widespread view that traders have asymmetric upside=
, that they have a call option on their trading: They benefit a lot from tr=
ading well but don=E2=80=99t lose that much from trading badly.If you are a=
 mid-level securities lawyer in the structured notes division of a big inve=
stment bank, two things that might happen are:=09You will carefully tick al=
l the boxes=C2=A0in a finicky and complicated business, allowing your bank =
to continue its program of issuing structured notes. The bank will make a l=
ot of money from structured notes, and you will be paid reasonably well, bu=
t no one will be like =E2=80=9Coh you=E2=80=99re our hero, you made sure al=
l the forms were filled out correctly.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s just your job,=
 and you do your job, and whatever.=09You will forget to tick one box and t=
he bank will somehow lose $600 million on structured notes from a lack of b=
ox-ticking? I don=E2=80=99t even know what happens to you in this case. I g=
uess you get fired? For losing the bank $600 million? Intuitively=C2=A0you =
seem to=C2=A0have asymmetric downside; you have written a put option on you=
r securities lawyering.=C2=A0But maybe not? Like, you don=E2=80=99t even ma=
ke enough money for firing you to be satisfying, or to feel commensurate wi=
th the $600 million loss; they might just not bother firing you. You might =
be too cursed for your bosses to get close enough to fire you. You might sp=
end the rest of your days walking aimlessly around the office as everyone s=
curries away to avoid your evil vibes. Maybe a few of the traders will befr=
iend you, though. A lawyer who loses $600 million on a trade is a rare beas=
t, and much cooler to traders than all the=C2=A0boring regular lawyers who =
don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0lose money.If you are a mid-level structured-notes lawye=
r, the first outcome is=C2=A0overwhelmingly=C2=A0likely; in fact I think it=
 describes the career of every mid-level structured-notes lawyer who ever s=
tructured a note. Except one!As part of its structured products business, B=
arclays Bank PLC (=E2=80=9CBBPLC=E2=80=9D), a subsidiary of Barclays PLC (=
=E2=80=9CBPLC=E2=80=9D), is a frequent issuer of structured notes and excha=
nge traded notes in the United States and elsewhere. These securities are o=
ften issued to meet actual and anticipated client demand for such securitie=
s.BBPLC has determined that the securities offered and sold under its US sh=
elf registration statement during a period of approximately one year exceed=
ed the registered amount (such excess, the =E2=80=9CAffected Securities=E2=
=80=9D)=C2=A0giving rise to a right of rescission among certain purchasers =
of Affected Securities requiring BBPLC to repurchase the Affected Securitie=
s at their original purchase price. As a result, BBPLC has elected to condu=
ct a rescission offer to eligible purchasers of the Affected Securities. De=
tails of the rescission offer will be published by BBPLC in due course.Base=
d on current market prices of the Affected Securities and the estimated poo=
l of potentially eligible purchasers electing to participate in the resciss=
ion offer, Barclays expects the rescission losses (net of tax) to be c.=C2=
=A3450m and the CET1 ratio of BPLC and its consolidated subsidiaries to be =
in the middle of the 13-14% target range as at 31 March 2022. This reflects=
 a c.14 bps reduction from the estimated loss and a further c.15 bps reduct=
ion due to an increase in risk weighted assets in respect of short-term hed=
ging arrangements designed to manage the risks to Barclays arising out of t=
he rescission offer.A footnote adds: =E2=80=9CIn August 2019, BBPLC registe=
red US$20.8bn in maximum aggregate offering price of securities (the =E2=80=
=98Registered Amount=E2=80=99) and has exceeded the Registered Amount by ap=
proximately US$15.2bn.=E2=80=9DThe technicalities of this are like =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0I wish I had some cool story to tell here, but this is the opposit=
e of a cool story. This is: If you want to sell securities to the public, i=
ncluding structured notes and exchange-traded notes, you have to register t=
he sales of those securities with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commissi=
on. If you are a tech startup looking to sell stock to the public for the f=
irst time, this is an =E2=80=9Cinitial public offering=E2=80=9D and is a bi=
g fraught emotional moment. If you are already a giant public global bank l=
ike Barclays, and you sell billions of dollars of bonds and structured note=
s and other things every year, it is just boring administrative work.You fi=
le a =E2=80=9Cshelf registration statement=E2=80=9D saying, in essence, =E2=
=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re going to sell various assorted securities over the next=
 few years.=E2=80=9D This is a simple document describing all possible secu=
rities in vague and general terms, and it includes=C2=A0some very large arb=
itrary number for how many securities you might sell.=C2=A0(Barclays put=C2=
=A0$20,081,600,000 in its 2019 shelf registration statement.) And every tim=
e you sell some structured notes or ETNs or whatever, you do a =E2=80=9Cshe=
lf takedown=E2=80=9D (metaphorically, you take the registration statement d=
own from the shelf, you use it to sell stuff, and you put it back on the sh=
elf) and use some of that capacity. When you do a takedown, you=C2=A0write =
a =E2=80=9Cprospectus supplement=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cpricing supplement=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0describing the actual terms of the particular notes that you=E2=
=80=99re issuing, to supplement the generic shelf registration statement; y=
ou file the supplement with the SEC so that investors can read about whatev=
er structured note=C2=A0they=E2=80=99re buying.=C2=A0Ideally you=E2=80=99d =
KEEP TRACK OF HOW MUCH YOU ISSUE, and subtract each issuance from the $20.1=
 billion you started with, and when that $20.1 billion gets down to, you kn=
ow, $2 billion, you file another shelf registration statement with the SEC =
saying =E2=80=9Cwe might do another $20 billion of stuff.=E2=80=9D And that=
 new shelf registration is quickly approved by the SEC,[1] and nobody think=
s too much about it, and then you can sell $20 billion more stuff, and the =
