A weird archaism of American corporate law is that companies have to write =
down, fairly early in their histories, the maximum number of shares of stoc=
k they can have outstanding, and then that number can only be changed by a =
vote of shareholders. You=E2=80=99re in your garage setting up your little =
startup =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, more plausibly, you=E2=80=99re taking that start=
up public as a medium-sized company =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the lawyers are like=
 =E2=80=9Cwhat is the most shares you could ever possibly want to issue=E2=
=80=9D and you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9CI dunno, two billion?=E2=80=9D You =
pick some comically large number and then, you hope, never worry about it a=
gain.[7] And then sometimes things go wrong and your stock price goes down =
to $0.25 and you need to raise a few hundred million dollars and the lawyer=
s are like =E2=80=9Cyou are out of shares=E2=80=9D and it=E2=80=99s really =
the dumbest reason to be unable to raise money.[8]Conversely if you write d=
own that you=E2=80=99ll never issue more than 2 billion shares, in the back=
 of your mind you are probably thinking of some normal share price and mult=
iplying it by 2 billion and thinking =E2=80=9Cwell that is a lot of money.=
=E2=80=9D Like: If your stock gets to $200 and you issue all 2 billion shar=
es you will be a $400 billion company and that will be a huge wild success,=
 and when future-you is running a $400 billion company, you will be so happ=
y and fulfilled that =E2=80=9Cnot enough authorized shares=E2=80=9D will no=
t be a thing that you even think about.Or so you think now, in the garage, =
but in fact:On March 28, 2022, Tesla, Inc. (the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D o=
r =E2=80=9CTesla=E2=80=9D) announced its plan to request stockholder approv=
al at the upcoming 2022 Annual Meeting of Stockholders (the =E2=80=9CAnnual=
 Meeting=E2=80=9D) for an increase in the number of authorized shares of co=
mmon stock through an amendment to the Company=E2=80=99s Amended and Restat=
ed Certificate of Incorporation (the =E2=80=9CAmendment=E2=80=9D) in order =
to enable a stock split of the Company=E2=80=99s common stock in the form o=
f a stock dividend. Tesla=E2=80=99s Board of Directors (=E2=80=9CBoard=E2=
=80=9D) has approved the management proposal, but the stock dividend will b=
e contingent on final Board approval.Tesla has about 1.03 billion shares of=
 stock outstanding; it has 2 billion authorized shares. Its stock closed on=
 Friday at $1,010.64, giving it a market capitalization of about $1.04 tril=
lion. That is a high and annoying price for stock, and for various reasons =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0psychological appeal to small-dollar retail investors, appea=
l to small-dollar retail options=C2=A0traders, ease of employee compensatio=
n, being in the Dow =E2=80=94=C2=A0companies sometimes want lower and less =
annoying stock prices. Split the stock 10 for 1 and have a $101 stock price=
, that=E2=80=99s nice. (And Tesla did a 5-for-1 split in 2020.)=C2=A0But Te=
sla can=E2=80=99t split the stock 10 for 1, or even 2 for 1, because it is =
out of stock, so it has to ask shareholders for more. They=E2=80=99ll agree=
, of course; it=E2=80=99s fine. It=E2=80=99s just silly and nice. Tesla wro=
te down the maximum amount of stock it could ever need, and it needs more b=
ecause it did too well.By the way, this is different from the Barclays thin=
g! The problem is not Tesla=E2=80=99s securities registration=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s very easy =E2=80=94=C2=A0but rather the number of s=
hares authorized in its corporate charter. You have to list your number of =
