s are marked. If you bought a note for $10 million and now it has gone down=
 and is worth=C2=A0$8 million, Barclays will pay you $10 million and take b=
ack the note; that counts as a $2 million loss.[4] Bloomberg=E2=80=99s top =
four holders on the HDS page are=C2=A0SIG Holdings LLC (i.e. Susquehanna In=
ternational Group), Citadel Advisors LLC, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Jane=
 Street Group LLC.[5] I assume that most structured notes are essentially o=
ne-off issuances to private-wealth clients. So some Barclays salesperson sa=
id to some client =E2=80=9Chey would you like a structured note that pays 6=
.5% but loses money if the Nasdaq, Russell 2000 and Dow all go down a lot,=
=E2=80=9D and the client said =E2=80=9Csure,=E2=80=9D and the client bought=
 $2.7 million of it and that was one pricing supplement.=C2=A0[6] Here I am=
 relying on Barclays=E2=80=99s press release; it=E2=80=99s not like I have =
actually built this spreadsheet. Seems tedious.[7] As far as I know the onl=
y reason not to write down, like, 400 trillion is that it=E2=80=99s embarra=
ssing to have a weird number in your public reports, even if it doesn=E2=80=
=99t matter? Delaware =E2=80=94=C2=A0where most big companies are incorpora=
ted =E2=80=94=C2=A0does charge its corporate franchise tax based in part on=
 number of authorized shares, but the cap on that is $200,000 per year and =
that kicks in at a relatively normal number.[8] You can find your way aroun=
d it. Issue preferred stock, get a shareholder vote, that sort of thing, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s annoying.[9] In my old job helping companies raise money by =
selling equity-linked instruments, did I ever mess this up? Yes, yes I did.=
 But we always caught it well before, like, launching the deal. (And then w=
e=E2=80=99d find annoying ways around it.)
