<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Oops</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a high-powered trader at a =
big investment bank, two things that might happen are:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">You might make $600 million for your bank this year, o=
r</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You might lose $600 million for =
your bank this year.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Neither is very =
likely, particularly not in this more boring post-crisis world, but either =
is possible. If you make $600 million that=E2=80=99s good and you=E2=80=99l=
l get a huge bonus. If you lose $600 million that=E2=80=99s bad and you=E2=
=80=99ll=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>get fired, though it depends, and anyw=
ay you=E2=80=99ll have a cool war story that will <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27177853.265603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvbWF5YmUtZ2FtZXN0b3AtaXMtZ29vZC=
1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291c=
mNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBec77908c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> quickly</a> get you <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27177853.265603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMjYvZXh4b24taGFzLWEtdG9=
1Z2gtZ3JlZW4tYWN0aXZpc3Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyODIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT=
1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMzI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnb=
j1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb319ab05" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> another big job=
</a> somewhere else. There is a widespread view that traders have asymmetri=
c upside, that they have a call option on their trading: They benefit a lot=
 from trading well but don=E2=80=99t lose that much from trading badly.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a mid-level securities lawyer in th=
e structured notes division of a big investment bank, two things that might=
 happen are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; =
margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You will carefully ti=
ck all the boxes=C2=A0in a finicky and complicated business, allowing your =
bank to continue its program of issuing structured notes. The bank will mak=
e a lot of money from structured notes, and you will be paid reasonably wel=
l, but no one will be like =E2=80=9Coh you=E2=80=99re our hero, you made su=
re all the forms were filled out correctly.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s just your=
 job, and you do your job, and whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">You will forget to tick one box and the bank will somehow lose $600 =
million on structured notes from a lack of box-ticking? I don=E2=80=99t eve=
n know what happens to you in this case. I guess you get fired? For losing =
the bank $600 million? Intuitively=C2=A0you seem to=C2=A0have asymmetric do=
wnside; you have written a put option on your securities lawyering.=C2=A0Bu=
t maybe not? Like, you don=E2=80=99t even make enough money for firing you =
to be satisfying, or to feel commensurate with the $600 million loss; they =
might just not bother firing you. You might be too cursed for your bosses t=
o get close enough to fire you. You might spend the rest of your days walki=
ng aimlessly around the office as everyone scurries away to avoid your evil=
 vibes. Maybe a few of the traders will befriend you, though. A lawyer who =
loses $600 million on a trade is a rare beast, and much cooler to traders t=
han all the=C2=A0boring regular lawyers who don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0lose money.<=
/li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a mid-level structured-not=
es lawyer, the first outcome is=C2=A0<em>overwhelmingly=C2=A0</em>likely; i=
n fact I think it describes the career of every mid-level structured-notes =
lawyer who ever structured a note. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/27177853.265603/aHR0cHM6Ly9ob21lLmJhcmNsYXlzL2NvbnRlbnQvZG=
FtL2hvbWUtYmFyY2xheXMvZG9jdW1lbnRzL2ludmVzdG9yLXJlbGF0aW9ucy9JUk5ld3NQcmVzZ=
W50YXRpb25zLzIwMjJOZXdzLzIwMjIwMzI4LUltcGFjdC1vZiUyMG92ZXItaXNzdWFuY2UtdW5k=
ZXItQkJQTEMtVVMtU2hlbGYucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBed85b9eb" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Exc=
ept one</a>!</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As part of its str=
uctured products business, Barclays Bank PLC (=E2=80=9CBBPLC=E2=80=9D), a s=
ubsidiary of Barclays PLC (=E2=80=9CBPLC=E2=80=9D), is a frequent issuer of=
 structured notes and exchange traded notes in the United States and elsewh=
ere. These securities are often issued to meet actual and anticipated clien=
t demand for such securities.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BBPLC has det=
ermined that the securities offered and sold under its US shelf registratio=
n statement during a period of approximately one year exceeded the register=
ed amount (such excess, the =E2=80=9CAffected Securities=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0giv=
ing rise to a right of rescission among certain purchasers of Affected Secu=
rities requiring BBPLC to repurchase the Affected Securities at their origi=
nal purchase price. As a result, BBPLC has elected to conduct a rescission =
offer to eligible purchasers of the Affected Securities. Details of the res=
cission offer will be published by BBPLC in due course.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Based on current market prices of the Affected Securities and =
the estimated pool of potentially eligible purchasers electing to participa=
te in the rescission offer, Barclays expects the rescission losses (net of =
tax) to be c.=C2=A3450m and the CET1 ratio of BPLC and its consolidated sub=
sidiaries to be in the middle of the 13-14% target range as at 31 March 202=
2. This reflects a c.14 bps reduction from the estimated loss and a further=
 c.15 bps reduction due to an increase in risk weighted assets in respect o=
f short-term hedging arrangements designed to manage the risks to Barclays =
arising out of the rescission offer.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">A footnote adds: =E2=80=9CIn August 2019, BBPLC registered US$20.8bn=
 in maximum aggregate offering price of securities (the =E2=80=98Registered=
 Amount=E2=80=99) and has exceeded the Registered Amount by approximately U=
S$15.2bn.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The technicalities of th=
is are like =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I wish I had some cool story to tell here, but t=
his is the opposite of a cool story. This is: If you want to sell securitie=
s to the public, including structured notes and exchange-traded notes, you =
have to register the sales of those securities with the U.S. Securities and=
 Exchange Commission. If you are a tech startup looking to sell stock to th=
e public for the first time, this is an =E2=80=9Cinitial public offering=E2=
=80=9D and is a big fraught emotional moment. If you are already a giant pu=
blic global bank like Barclays, and you sell billions of dollars of bonds a=
nd structured notes and other things every year, it is just boring administ=
rative work.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You file a =E2=80=9Cshelf regi=
stration statement=E2=80=9D saying, in essence, =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re goin=
g to sell various assorted securities over the next few years.=E2=80=9D Thi=
s is a simple document describing all possible securities in vague and gene=
ral terms, and it includes=C2=A0some very large arbitrary number for how ma=
ny securities you might sell.=C2=A0(Barclays put=C2=A0$20,081,600,000 in it=
s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27177853.265603/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzMxMjA3MC8wMDAxMTkzMTI=
1MTkxNzM3OTMvZDc1NjE2MWRmMy5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7ea3b56b" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>2019 shelf registration statement</a>.) And every time you sell some struc=
tured notes or ETNs or whatever, you do a =E2=80=9Cshelf takedown=E2=80=9D =
(metaphorically, you take the registration statement down from the shelf, y=
ou use it to sell stuff, and you put it back on the shelf) and use some of =
that capacity. When you do a takedown, you=C2=A0write a =E2=80=9Cprospectus=
 supplement=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cpricing supplement=E2=80=9D=C2=A0describin=
g the actual terms of the particular notes that you=E2=80=99re issuing, to =
supplement the generic shelf registration statement; you file the supplemen=
t with the SEC so that investors can read about whatever structured note=C2=
=A0they=E2=80=99re buying.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ideally yo=
u=E2=80=99d KEEP TRACK OF HOW MUCH YOU ISSUE, and subtract each issuance fr=
om the $20.1 billion you started with, and when that $20.1 billion gets dow=
n to, you know, $2 billion, you file another shelf registration statement w=
ith the SEC saying =E2=80=9Cwe might do another $20 billion of stuff.=E2=80=
=9D And that new shelf registration is quickly approved by the SEC,[1] and =
nobody thinks too much about it, and then you can sell $20 billion more stu=
ff, and the numbers are all arbitrary and this is all administrative.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And if you just forget =E2=80=94=C2=A0if some ju=
nior person in the internal legal team leaves, and forgets to pass along th=
e =E2=80=9Cshelfcapacityleft_07.xls=E2=80=9D spreadsheet to her successor, =
and it stops being updated =E2=80=94=C2=A0then, uh. Then, at first,=C2=A0<e=
m>nothing happens</em>. No bell rings. The SEC doesn=E2=80=99t call you up =
to be like =E2=80=9CI see you are selling securities illegally.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0(They don=E2=80=99t really keep track either.) The=C2=A0<em>buyers=C2=A0=
</em>of these notes don=E2=80=99t notice: You are still (you think) doing s=
helf takedowns; you are still writing pricing supplements describing the ne=
w notes and filing them with the SEC. The buyers have access to all the inf=
ormation they would have had if you had filed a new shelf; nobody is <em>ha=
rmed=C2=A0</em>by any of this. You just keep bopping along as though everyt=
hing was fine, and then one day a new junior analyst starts on the legal te=
am and finds the =E2=80=9Cshelfcapacityleft_07.xls=E2=80=9D spreadsheet in =
a folder and asks the vice president =E2=80=9Chey what is this,=E2=80=9D an=
d the VP looks, and she realizes what it is, and they check the math 20 tim=
es because it seems too horrible to be true, and then they all leave for th=
e bar at noon because it is not a fixable error and they will miss each oth=
er when they=E2=80=99re all fired tomorrow.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>It is not a fixable error because the rules are harsh, and there is no no-=
harm-no-foul rule for illegal securities offerings. If you sell securities =
without a valid registration statement =E2=80=94=C2=A0as Barclays did =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0then you have to offer to buy the securities back at the price =
you sold them for. If the securities were structured notes and ETNs =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that is, bets that some index will go up or down, or weird exotic =
options bets =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if you don=E2=80=99t catch the mistake for =
a whole year, then some of them will have gone down a lot. You sold them fo=
r $100 and now they are worth $50 and you have to buy them back at $100. (O=
thers will have gone=C2=A0<em>up=C2=A0</em>a lot, but you don=E2=80=99t get=
 to buy <em>those</em> back at par: You have to offer to rescind all of you=
r sales, but the holders can decline.) You can call up the SEC and say =E2=
=80=9Cwe messed up a little bit but no one was harmed, sorry,=E2=80=9D and =
the SEC will say =E2=80=9Cah yes we see, we understand, no one was harmed a=
nd you didn=E2=80=99t mean it,=E2=80=9D and they will feel sorry for you, b=
ut they will still make you offer to buy back all the ETNs. And then you=E2=
=80=99ll lose 450 million pounds.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This i=
s just, like, securities regulation is complicated, and if you forget to do=
 a complicated thing then you might have to give an arbitrary amount of mon=
ey to an arbitrary group of people. I don=E2=80=99t know what to tell you. =
