<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Fade</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way a block trade often works is t=
hat a big seller =E2=80=94=C2=A0a public company, a private equity backer o=
f the company, a group of big investors in the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0comes=
 to one or more banks and says =E2=80=9Chey I might be interested in sellin=
g a block, get ready.=E2=80=9D And the banks think about their capacity to =
do the trade, and what they think the stock is worth. And then at 4:01 p.m.=
, right after the market closes, the seller comes back to the banks and say=
s =E2=80=9Cokay give me your price.=E2=80=9D And the banks bid for the stoc=
k, and whoever bids the highest price wins and gets the block of stock. And=
 then at like 4:15 p.m. the winning bank goes out and calls its big custome=
rs and tries to sell them the stock it just bought. If it sells all of the =
stock, that evening (or the following morning before the market opens), for=
 a higher price than it bid, it makes money and has done a successful block=
 trade. If it can=E2=80=99t resell all the stock before the market opens, t=
hen the block is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chung=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0the bank is stu=
ck with the risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0and that=E2=80=99s not a great outcome. (Co=
uld be fine, though, if the stock goes up the next day! But that=E2=80=99s =
not generally the goal of block trading.) If it resells at a lower price th=
an it paid, then it loses money because it priced the block too high.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might notice a problem. The problem is that =
the seller talks to the banks twice: once to give them some sort of warning=
 that a block is coming, and again at 4:01 p.m. to ask for their bids. (The=
 first call might come the morning of the same day, or mid-afternoon, or co=
nceivably as much as weeks in advance depending on the need for securities =
filings, financial advice, etc.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If y=
ou are a bank, and you have some warning that you=E2=80=99re going to be as=
ked to bid on a block, the main thing you will want to know is: Which of my=
 clients will want to buy this block? Your job, in buying the block, is to =
resell it quickly. If you know that a lot of your clients want to buy the s=
tock, then you can be confident of reselling it quickly.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">So you might just call them up and ask them? This is somewher=
e between =E2=80=9Cfrowned upon=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cillegal,=E2=80=9D dep=
ending on the specific circumstances, but it would help you with your bid. =
Perhaps you ask them hypothetically, or you ask them their feelings about a=
 sector generally, or you survey them about a bunch of hypothetical blocks =
and sneak the real one in there. Get, as they say, some =E2=80=9Cmarket col=
or=E2=80=9D before you have to bid on the block.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">There is another benefit of tipping your hand a bit. In general your =
bid, at 4:01 p.m., will be evaluated against the closing price of the stock=
, at 4 p.m. You will probably bid less than the closing price, because the =
block represents a lot of new supply, and you=E2=80=99ll need to sell it at=
 a discount to get clients to buy it. But the tighter the discount, the bet=
ter your bid looks. If the stock closes at $100 and you bid $99.25, that=E2=
=80=99s a nice impressive bid, a tight discount of less than 1%. If you bid=
 $92 you are not taking this seriously and you are going to annoy the clien=
t. If you bid $100 =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you think that you can resell the stoc=
k for the closing price, or even a higher price =E2=80=94=C2=A0then everyon=
e will be very impressed and you=E2=80=99ll probably win the block. Nobody =
expects you to bid $102. The closing price is the anchor for the block pric=
e; a bid at a slight (or even no) discount to the close is a good bid, whil=
e a bid that is far below the close is a bad bid.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">But when you get that first call, at 9 a.m. or 2 p.m. or whatever, y=
ou don=E2=80=99t know the closing price yet. If the stock is at $100 at 2 p=
.m., and then it has a little accident and it closes at $93, and you bid $9=
2.50 for the block, then hey that=E2=80=99s a really tight discount, good j=
ob. If =E2=80=A6=C2=A0you were to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0<em>cause</em> =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0that accident =E2=80=A6=C2=A0then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, you might go t=
o jail, but you might also be able to make a lot of money on block trades? =
If the stock drops to $93 in the last two hours of trading, <em>because you=
 told your clients a block was coming and they dumped the stock</em>,=C2=A0=
and you buy the stock at a tight discount to the closing price, you=E2=80=
=99ll have a good chance of reselling it at $93 or more, because that $93 p=
rice is in some sense not real; it just reflects people getting ready for t=
he block trade. The price drop=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>the discount; you don=
=E2=80=99t need to buy the stock at a discount to the closing price because=
 the closing price already reflects the supply of the block. Because you to=
ld everyone about it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27177853.265603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
